               <desc type="building-data" xml:lang="en">
                  <p source="#bibl000056c-3" source="#bibl000056c-2">
                     Fachuan (Dharma Boat) Main Hall is a two-story pavilion with a  hip-gable roof <term ref="/keyword/k000143">(xieshanding 歇山頂)</term>). The hall originally spans five bays in width and four rafters in depth. The internal column grid adopts the jinxiang dou dicao（金廂鬥底槽) arrangement. The hall is built on a raised platform projecting 40 cm beyond the exterior wall. Front terrace <term ref="/keyword/k000123">(yuetai月臺)</term> is 12 cm lower than larger platform, and approximately 50 cm above ground level (Jiake 2015, 56). The platform structure itself is constructed of brick and stone, with its surface paved with square-cut stone slabs. The central bay of the hall is wider than the secondary bays, and the secondary bays is wider than the corner bays. The extended front terrace was likely designed for Buddhist rituals and is believed to have once held an incense burner. In 1966, the entire hall and the statues inside it were destroyed. Today, the only remains are four broken pieces of the original stone pedestal(s). </p>
                  
                  <p source="#bibl000056c-2">
                     Originally, there was a bronze Buddha triad with a central Buddha framed by two Bodhisattvas on a stone “boat”(chuan 船). According to the Fozu Tongji 佛祖统纪)and Cefu Yuangui 册府元龟, it is speculated that two of the Buddhist activities ordered by the <term ref="/keyword/k00082">Tang</term> Dynasty were held in the Fachuan Main Hall.</p>
                  
                  <p source="#bibl000056c-2">
                     The sculpture and stone boat were supported by a Sumeru-style pedestal (Xumizuo 須彌座). The remains of the pedestal are divided into four sections, which are engraved with lotus petals, cloud patterns, and guardian figures.  Scholars believe that the pedestal was repurposed from an earlier stone architectural component. These four segments are the only surviving relics from the Fachuan Main Hall of Kaiyuan Monastery and are currently housed at Longxing Monastery. </p>
                  
                 </desc>
